column168: At approximately 1500 hrs on Monday March 4, 2013 a leak was reported coming from the top of tank car FURX 130333. Appropriate notifications were made and KCS emergency responders were activated.     Upon further inspection, tank car FURX 130333 was found with a defective liquid line valve which had bent/deformed stop tabs. Due to the defective stop tabs, the valve was placed past the closed position, placing the ball valve in the slightly reversed open position. The afternoon sun built up enough internal pressure to push the liquid lading past the open liquid valve and then by the unsecured secondary closure plug. The secondary closure plug threads were not prepared with Teflon tape.    After the valve was placed in the closed position, the liquid product held on top of the ball valve indicating that the valve was operational--if positioned correctly. The tank car was vented, the liquid valve was opened to allow the lading trapped above the valve to drop back into the tank car. Then the valve was placed in the closed position and the plug was tightened tool tight. The protective housing tamper seal" Calumet-022069" was removed and replaced with seal number "0237728."   The estimated release was one gallon.     During the response, it was noted that the vapor valve also had a defective stop tab. It is suspected that the load/unload operators are stepping on these valve handles to cause the damage to the stop tabs.     *The lading contained in this tank car is VM+P Naphatha, which is an automotive type paint thinner, which flashes off (evaporates) very quickly. There is no inhalation hazard associated with this type of outdoor release. The primary hazard associated with this commodity is a low flash point and possible ignition of the flammable liquid.     The responder reported the defect and release to the shipper and they will have the valve replaced after the car is unloaded. The DOT specification package is now in compliance and can proceed safely in transportation.    *KCS emergency services were activated to provide for railroad safety qualified services to mitigate this emergency (e.g., yard service interruption, Critical Incident Desk notifications, emergency response, management oversight, train/yard crew delay, and regulatory notification reports).  KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 and KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 will apply.     * No injuries reported    File Note Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact  consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk q
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities,   and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable.    For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence   of unsafe transportation conditions.    The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs. To improve communications the shipper can provide contact information in this web site (Contact Network) to better facilitate incident response and post incident communications as applicable.

column168: ON 3/5/13 AT APPROXIMATELY 0400AM, CLT DOCKWORKER OPENED TRAIL 586246 AND IMMEDIATELY NOTICED CORROSIVE DRUM LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER DOCKWORKER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE ASSISTANT SERVICE CENTER MANAGER IN CHARLOTTE. LOCATED THE LEAKING DRUM AND TURNED IT ON THE DOCK TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE. THE 33 GALLON DRUM DID NOT APPEAR TO HAVE BEEN PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT, BUT DID HAVE VISIBLE NAIL HOLES ON THE BOTTOM OF THE LEAKING DURM. IT APPEARED TO HAVE PUNCTURED BY THE NAILS UNDERNEATH DRUM ON SKID. REGIONAL SAFETY MANAGER FOR CHARLOTTE TERMINAL. HEATH CARRELL WAS THEN NOTIFIED. AFTER BEING INFORMED OF SPILL, A HAZMAT RESPONSE COMPANY WAS DISPATCHED TO CLEAN UP SPILL.
column169: THE SPILL SEEMED TO BE THE RESULT OF POOR PACKAGING BY THE SHIPPER. LOOSE NAILS UNDER A SOFT-BOTTOM & HEAVY DRUM RESULTED IN A PUNCTURE AND A LEAK. SHIPPER MAY WANT TO USE A BARRIER SUCH AS THICK CARDBOARD UNDERNEATH PLASTIC DRUMS WHEN LOADED ON WOODEN PALLETS WITH NAILS.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services individual was enroute from shipper's location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a ten-day facility for the purposes of consoidating less than truck load quantities onto a single transport vehicle for continued transportation.  During the transfer operation a drum lid broke off while being lifted with a drum dolly grabber.  The drum fell a few inches to the floor of the vehicle.  No product was released from the vehicle.  Vermeculite was immediately applied. Facility personnel assembled a response team whom proceeded to place the compromised container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once completed, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of cracking, leaking, or staining that would indicate an aged or compromised drum was observed.   CHES personnedl have been advised to continually be diligent in their inspection of containers prior to loading and/or tranporting.

Mr. Dedow reported his observation to Conrail's Risk Manager A. Richter.  Mr. Richter contacted Hepaco-React, Conrail's emergency response contractor, to respond and remediate the car.    Further inspection by Hepaco-React noted approximately 1 gallon of product laying on top of the car, of which some had dripped down both sides.  Found car under vaccum.  Determined that the product residue was result of poor unloading and inspection practices prior to offering the car in transportation after it had been unloaded.  Car was cleaned and car okayed to be forwarded onto original destination.

column168: FRA and WV State Inspectors conducting a joint inspection smelled a "fishy" odor when walking track DI-10 which contained several residue amine cars for loading by Dupont.  Dupont and NS Environmental were notified and Dupont sent a team from their Belle, WV plant to investigate.  They found tank car PROX 30342 leaking from the protective housing with the use of a SO2 cylinder.  They opened the protective housing and found all three valves (two liquid and one vapor) to be cracked open and the plugs not wrench tight.  Dupont closed the valves, removed, cleaned, and re-taped the plugs, securing them wrench tight.  Car was rechecked with SO2 and found to be secure.

column168: At approximately 4:45PM on 3/16/2013 it was observed that petroleum crude oil was leaking from the top of tank car UTLX 46529 in the KCS Beaumont Yard in Beaumont, TX. Emergency notifications were made and responders activated.    Upon inspection by responder, it was noted that the source of the leak was from the liquid line 4 bolt flange, 2 bolts were less than tool tight. Responder tightened the flange to appropriate tightness and performed an initial cleanup of lading on side of tank car. Responder de-mobilized due to lack of daylight and returned on 3/17/2013 in the morning. Responder performed final cleanup and notified KCS. The tank car was then released back into regular transportation.    * No injuries reported    File Note Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact  consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities,   and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable.    For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence   of unsafe transportation conditions.

column168: On 03/062013, container FCIU 456401 was discovered leaking product out of the right front corner of the container. On March 4, 2013, at 0601 hrs., a car inspector at the CSX Avon Terminal, Avon, IN, noticed an odor near UTLX 910591, a residue tank car of UN1077, Propylene. The tank car was isolated and the shipper, Citgo Petroleum Corp., was notified via Chemtrec report #2013-03-04-00070. Summit Contracting, a CSX emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene. Summit personnel inspected the car and could hear hissing from within the pressure housing. The housing was opened and the "B" end liquid line valve was found partially open and the secondary securement plug less than tool tight. The shipper representative, Michelle Walker, Citgo Petroleum (832-486-4184) was notified of the situation found. The release was secured and UTLX 910591 was released for disposition.  This incident did not require a special switching move.    NARRI: 5(4+5+0)x(2+0) = 90  Cause code:119

column168: While making a delivery, a sodium bisulfite tote failed releasing the contents onto the roadway.  The driver noticed the problem from the side mirror and pulled to the shoulder of the highway to contact the Plant Manager of the incident.  The Aurora Police Department and Fire Department arrived when he was on the phone with the facility.  While on the phone with the plant manager, the Department of Transportation arrived and closed the highway.    The plant manager contacted the corporate office within 15-minutes of the incident.  Although this was not a RQ incident, the CDPHE was contacted to notify them of the spill and road closure.  The Environmental Affairs Manager contacted SRS for assistance in getting a local contractor onsite in a short amount of time.  Belfor, a local waste contractor, arrived to remediate the area by alternating between washing and vacuuming the roadway of product residue.  Belfor was onsite for approximately 8-hours.    There were no injuries reported.  Investigation is ongoing.
column169: Facility no longer accepts totes older than 5-years from an outside vendor.    Investigation ongoing so additional corrective actions may be initiated.

column168: Mgr. Lerch responded to reported leaking tank car UTLX 209021.  Inspection of car revealed product leaking from the 165 pound reclosing pressure relief device.  Continued inspection revealed car was over loaded causing valve to function with 200 pounds of internal pressure.  Mgr. Lerch gagged reclosing pressure relief device which secured car from further release.  Approximately 130 barrels of product was immediately reduced from the car into a vacuum truck which yielded appropriate outage.  Sides of car and spill site were cleaned and remediated.  Upon completion of clean-up, car was released to continue onto destination.  Reduced product transported to a shipper designated facility.
column169: Ascertain outage of empty residue car prior to loading to ensure car is not overloaded during loading process.

column168: On March 15, 2013, a Veolia employee was using an electric pallet jack to move a 275 gal tote(IBC) from one trailer to another. While moving the tote into the trailer, the employee accidentally steered the tote against the side wall of the trailer. An aluminum side panel for placarding, which is attached to the tote, was squeezed against the side of the receiving trailer and tote, and subsequently a bottom sharp edge of the panel punctured the side wall of the tote spilling an estimated 20 gallons of material.  The puncture in the tote was located in the middle side of the tote.  The release lasted approximately one hour and the material that leaked was cleaned up and sent to a proper waste disposal facility.  The remaining waste in the punctured tote was transferred into a new tote for disposal.  The punctured tote was sent to a proper waste disposal facility.
column169: Veolia employees at Schenectady, NY were trained to not steer totes up against the side wall of trailers when loading and offloading using an electric pallet jack. The Veolia employee involved in this incident was given electric pallet jack re-training.

column168: A California PUC Hazardous Material Inspector inspecting an inbound BNSF train in the railyard reported entrained tank car UTLX 645308 with a loose manway cover securement bolt with evidence of a commodity leak from the manway closure. Immediate inspection by BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders confirmed the loose manway securement bolt. Intact shipper seal CANEXUS 039017 at the manway closure was removed and the manway was opened to inspect the manway gasket condition. No manway gasket was present and the responders applied a new manway gasket and properly secured all manway securement bolts. BNSF seal 06157599 was applied at the manway closure. Response was concluded by 1155 hrs. PST, 3/06/2013. The commodity spillage on UTLX 645308 had dried and no ground impact from any spillage was evident.

While traveling, a vehicle rollover resulted in the release of approximately 6,160 gallons of condensate.  Free product released to the roadside soils, down a slight embankment, and into a dry stream bed.  Fuller Environmental of Canton, Texas responded to assess the site, and pumped remaining free product from the damaged tank.  Approximately 840 gallons of virgin product were pumped from the tanker.  Fuller Environmental proceeded to recover the free product, which had pooled in constructed collection pits, and secured the site pending excavation activities.  Fuller Environmental returned to the site, excavated the impacted soils, and coordinated disposal of waste generated during response.  Excavation area was approximately 60 feet long by 20 feet wide.  Depth of soil contamination ranged from 7 feet to 9 feet in some areas.  Approximately 2,450 yards of soil were recovered during excavation.  Disposal was coordinated in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  Confirmation soil samples were pulled, and site was restored to preexisting condition.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.

WITHIN THE SHIPMENT APPEARED TO BE CONSUMER GOOD FROM BATH AND BODY WORKS AND VICTORIA SECRET; HAND SANITZER BOTH LARGE AND SMALL BOTTLES, BODY SPRAY/MISTS, PRESSURIZED SPRAY CONTAINERS AND OTHER FRAGRANCES, LOTIONS AND OTHER TYPES OF AIR FRESHNERS BODY SCENTS. column168: Container was set aside for load adjustment due to being unbalanced.  When the contractor opened the doors they found one drum hazardous material (1H1/Y1.4/100/12N) had released material.  The load of 26 drums was not properly blocked or braced and had been tied to the side of the container with a rope.  The drums had come loose and one had been crushed by other freight in the container.  When the load adjustment contractor determined that a hazardous materials spill had occurred, NS was notified and an environmental contractor was called in to respond.  Spilled material was cleaned up and re-drumed in salvage drums.  Undamaged drums were repacked in another container.

column168: During a routine mechanical inspection, NS car inspector noted product on the side of tank car RAIX 6452 appearing to be coming from the manway.  Car was moved to the spill pan and isolated.  NS Environmental and a contractor were notified.  Contractor opened the manway and found the flat manway gasket intact but was not able to secured the manway properly.  Contractor placed a second gasket on the nozzle and was able to secure the manway.  Car was shaken and no leakage was evident.  Contractor returned the following day to check repairs and found several bolts loose due gasket creep and the "ears" on the manway cover being bent.  The manway bolts would slip down the bent "ears" as the nuts were tightened.  Contents will be transfered and the car shopped.

column169: Root cause investigation reports:   1. Cargo tank trailer was not properly prepped per company policy after cleaning. Company procedure is that maintenance must secure external valves and wash out caps on trailer and seal each before loading.  2. Driver failed to adequately report that trailer was not properly prepped for loading and dispatch when notified that there may be a problem did not properly investigate and ensure procedures were followed  3. Procedures have been reviewed with driver and dispatcher.

column168: PROPANE TRANSPORT DRIVER FAILED TO MAINTAIN CONTROL IN A CURVE. TANK ROLLED OFF A BRIDGE AND FELL TO THE ROCKY GROUND BELOW. THE REAR HEAD OF THE TRAILER IMPACTED THE STONE AND WAS BENT AND CRACKED OPEN. THE CRACK WAS 4" LONG AND 1/16" WIDE. THE RELEASE LASTED 8 HOURS. column168: Section VI  The container (IBC serial number 1298-8) was filled with hazardous waste and prepared for shipment at building 48, 307 E. McCarty Street, Indianapolis, IN 46225. No issues were seen with the threaded fitting at the time of shipment either during preparation or loading. The container was then transported to building 82, 1297 S. White River Pkwy E. Dr., Indianapolis, IN 46225 for consolidation with other waste containers prior to transport by 2nd carrier to the final TSDF facility.     While the container was at building 82, dock personnel identified a small leak (less than 50ml) from the threaded fitting on the bottom of the container. The small spill was contained and cleaned up by Waste Management personnel immediately.   The waste contents in the container were transferred to another IBC for transport to final TSD facility. The empy container was then triple rinsed at building 82 and sent for repair.
column169: IBC serial number 1298-8 will be repaired and retested for DOT certification prior to use. Preventative measures taken will include continued use of preshipment checklist with added focus on threaded fittings.

column168: AN UNLOADER DROPPED A HAZMAT PACKAGE APPROXIMATELY 3 FEET ONTO THE IRREG CHUTE. SUPERVISOR NOTICED THAT THE CYLINDER INSIDE HAD STARTED LEAKING & NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I UTILIZED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS (NON-FLAMMABLE GAS) TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. I CONTAINERIZED THE LEAKING PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. THEN CHECKED THE VALVE TO SEE IF IT HAD OPENED. UPON FINDIMG THE VALVE CLOSED & INTACT, I TOOK THE CYLINDER OUT OF THE BOX & NOTICED A PUNCTURE HOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE METAL CYLINDER. 1 CLEANED UP THE LIQIUD ON THE FLOOR WITH CLAY-BASED ABSORBANT & ADDED ITOF THE GAS AS I TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA. FOLLOWING MY RESPONSE SHEET, I PLACED THE LEAKING CYLINDER OUTDOORS TO A WELL-VENTILATED AREA. I SOLIDIFIED ALL LIQUID IN THE LEFT FROM THE CYLINDER IN THE SPILL TRAY WITH CLAY-BASED ABSORBANT.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. Damaged tote was offloaded into recovery drums, neutralized product was recovered, and affected area was washed down.  Disposal was coordinated in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  Product was contained to impervious surface.  There was no impact to surface soils or threat to enter state waters.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.

column168: During a compliance inspection in the LAJ railyard, a California PUC inspector reported residue tank car UTLX 204424 hissing vapors from its vacuum relief valve (VRV) with no liquid release. Contract responders inspected UTLX 204424 finding the VRV venting vapors and attempts to reseat the VRV failed. Internal pressure within UTLX 204424 was reduced and the faulty VRV was removed. A pipe plug was inserted and secured in the vacated VRV orifice by 1940 hrs. PDT, 3/11/2013. Inspection of the removed VRV revealed that the VRV pressure seal or 'quad seal' was cut/damaged which allowed vapors to escape via the VRV. UTLX 204424 was directed to an UTC repair facility for VRV replacement.

column168: The driver had completed the transfer of the product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank using a pump. he closed all the valves, let the product skim down the inside of the trailer, opened valves again and cleared the lines.  he then disconnected the hose from the pump outlet, set it down and had walked away to get some paperwork.  When he came back, he realized that he had forgotten to close the valve on the storage tank the second time and the product back flowed out the hose.  The customer called out an emergency response vendor to clean it up.
column169: This was definitely human error.  The driver did not follow proper procedure and was brought into the office for remeidial training.

column168: Driver had to use 100' of hose to transfer product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  Before he hooked the hose up, he identified that one section of hose didn't have a gasket.  he replaced the gasket and started to unload.  As soon as the product started flowing, the section of hose with the replaced gasket started to leak.  The driver immediately shut down.  When he looked at the gasket better, he said it appeared to be a "hair" smaller than the normal gasket.  he replaced the gasket with a correctly sized one and completed the offload with no further leakage.
column169: The driver had picked up the gasket at one of our facilities but we were not able to determine why it was smaller.  we have not received any reports of similar incidents.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While at truckstop, a leak was discovered from the tanker. Upon investigation, it was determined the leak occurred due to a manufacturer defect on the bung. Free product released to the asphalt parking lot. Elko Sheriffs Department responded to assess the site, and applied absorbents to the free product, which contained to immediate area. Elko Fire Department was dispatched to respond, isolated the area, and closed off the truckstop as a precautionary measure. Clean Harbors Environmental of Carlin, Nevada was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Upon arrival on site, Clean Harbors assessed the area and took control of the incident. Leaking product had been contained to an impervious surface, and did not migrate to surface soils or threaten to enter waters of the state. A drum was placed under the leak, to prevent further contamination, area was isolated and secured, and truckstop was reopened for business. Clean Harbors applied additional absorbent to the asphalt lot, and proceeded to monitor and contain the leaking product, pending arrival of a clean certified tank for offload. Once clean tank arrived on site, Clean Harbors offloaded product from damaged tank, and pumped out virgin product from container drums into certified tank. Spent absorbent material was recovered into six (6) 55-gallon drums. Affected area was pressure washed and neutralized, and rinsate water was containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum. Disposal was coordinated in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Jeff Foster Trucking will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: Tank car UTLX 210644 in the railyard was reported with fresh commodity on its side shell that appeared to have emanated from its manway closure. UTLX 210644 deemed safe to move was isolated in the railyard awaiting detailed inspection and cleaning by contract responders. Later on 3/21/2013, contract responders inspected UTLX 210644 finding loose manway securement bolts. The manway gasket was inspected and found properly installed and serviceable. Responders closed the manway lid and properly tool tightened all 8 manway securement bolts. The intact shipper seal removed at the manway closure was replaced by seal numbered 2877203. The spillage on UTLX 210644 was cleaned using a hot water wash. The spent wash water was captured in catch basins placed under UTLX 210644 and earmarked for appropriate disposal along with other spent cleaning materials.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Customer drained their diked area before off loading was started but the concrete area was still damp.  Driver hooked 2 hoses together and the gasket with was at the connection failed and during the pump off material leaked out was was not detected due to the wet surface until some 3 gallons was released.  The hoses are 2" with cam-lock connections.  Once the leak was detected, the pump was shut down, valves closed on cargo tank.  Clean up was completed with customer response team.  After testing air with proper sampling meter, the all clear was given and the off load was completed, after driver replaced the bad gasket.
column169: The issue was a bad gasket in which the driver had spares with him.  Re-training with the drivers to ensure all gaskets are acceptable before off loading any product. This is part of a typical unloading routine.

column168: Driver was unloading product into underground storage tank.  He stuck the tank prior to beginning delivery, but miscalculated ullage.  The tank overfilled during unloading.  Overfill protection on the tank worked properly and engaged.  The hose fitting came loose, and product spilled.  Driver was in the cab of the tractor at the time and did not notice immediately.  An employee at the facility noticed the spill and immediately notified the driver.  The driver closed all valves and stopped flow of product from trailer.  Several other employees of the facility assisted with initial containment and clean up.  Spill pads and booms were deployed to contain.  Spill impacted asphalt, gravel, and storm drains.  A clean up company was called to complete clean up.
column169: Company policy requires all drivers to remain present at unloading areas during delivery.  Driver violated policy.  Driver was retrained on unloading procedures.  All company drivers were reminded of policy.  Additionally, all drivers were instructed to report damaged hose fittings immediately and to request repair or replacement.  Field Safety Supervisor is completing field observations of driver to ensure continued adherence to procedures.

column168: Unit 1 was towing unit 2 (hazmat vehicle) traveling southbound on FM1284.  Unit 3 was traveling westbound on Morton Elevator Road.  Unit 3 was struck on the passenger side by unit 1 after unit 3 disregarded the stop sign on Morton Elevator Road.  Authorities believe occupants of unit 3 died on impact from blunt force trauma.  All units traveled off of roadway to right.  Unit 2 sideswiped concrete utility pole.  The sideswipe ruptured cargo tank compartment and ignited flammable liquid.  All units were consumed by fire.  Driver of unit 1 escaped from truck-tractor cab and suffered major burn injury.      Approximately 70% percent of  flammable liquid was consumed by fire and remaining product was partially contained in remains of cargo tank compartments or spilled upon earthen shoulder of roadway.  Police, Fire and Environmental response personnel contained spilled product.  As soon as fire was extinguished, clean-up steps began to remove and dispose of remaining product and contaminated earth along roadway shoulder.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Tank car UTLX 207411 in the railyard was reported with fresh commodity on its side shell with no ground impact noted.  A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected UTLX 207411.and reported the leak source at the 165 psi pressure relief valve/device (PRD). Further examination of the PRD revealed that the valve stem was broken at its lower threaded area. UTLX 207411 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting installation of a replacement PRD and cleaning of the spillage on its side shell. No further commodity release was observed as UTLX 207411 remained motionless. On 3/11/2013, a contractor cleaned all the spillage from UTLX 207411 with spent cleaning materials earmarked for appropriate disposal.   As of 4/08/2013, the replacement PRD has been ordered and UTLX 207411 is still on hold awaiting the replacement PRD's arrival and installation.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: The tank car NATX 310422 was discovered releasing product from the man way while in a siding at Bossier City, LA at 10:00 A.M. on 3/13/2013.  Tom Robinson Manager of Hazardous Materials was called to investigate and discovered the tank car was releasing product from the man way nozzle cover not being properly secured. The tank car was also overfilled and reduced by approximately 3000 gallons.  The top and sides of the tank car were remediated and the car was rerouted to Shreveport to be unloaded.

column168: AA clerk did a visual check upon acceptance. Noticed the directional labels were not adhered too and boxes were wet. A noxious odor was omitted from the boxes. They X-rayed but could not determine the content. Air Waybill description: Ships spares Medicine-Not restricted.  The boxes were opened to find 10 bottles, 1 liter each of insecticidal liquid packed upside down and leaking. Another box containing 2 5kgs bottles of Formalin (34% to 37% Formaldehyde solution); the box too small for the bottles, were packed on its side and was just beginning to leak. 2" diameter stain was found inside of the box. Other liquid items packed among the 6 boxes were Ethanol, Saline Solution, Antiseptic Liquid, Aerosol Insect Killer, Sodium Chloride, Ceftriaxone Injection, Benzathine Penicillin Injection & Lignocaine Injection.    Total of 6 boxes, medical supplies to be flown to Madrid then trucked to Valencia, Spain, to be loaded on a ship.  "Glass - Handle with Care" directional labels were the only label used on the boxes.  Boxes were used boxes turned inside out, brown paint on the inside of one box to cover up the old label.  The manager on duty wrote up a report to go to the TSA and the boxes were placed in the Dangerous Goods Area of the cargo warehouse for the night. Placards were placed on the shipment "HOLD - Do not Move".  The next day, the items were placed in a ULD and placed outside due to the fumes. The FAA Security & Hazardous Materials Safety Team came out to inspect the shipment.

column168: At approximately 8:11 A.M. on 3/21/2013, a KCS employee noticed lading surrounding on the liquid loading line of tank car PLMX 135478. Appropriate notifications were made and Phillips 66 responder was activated.    Shipper responders remediated the situation before KCS repsonders arrived on site. Per the operator that responded to the leak and photos taken at the site, a leak was identified in the vicinity of the final plug thread area downstream of the valve on the liquid loading line. The valve was found to be tightly closed and no evidence of damage was noted.  The operator applied additional torque to the plug and was able stop all leaking, which was verified with a bubble test.     At approximately 9:34 AM Louisiana State Police along with a Phillips 66 Lake Charles employee called an all clear on the railcar leak.  A Phillips 66 Area D loader was able to tighten the area of the leak and this was verified with a soap / water solution.      The shipper has taken care of the One Time Movement Approval process.    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier.Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence.     It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs. To improve communications the shipper can provide contact information in this web site (Contact Network) to better facilitate incident response and post incident communications as applicable.

column17: M V BONN EXPRESS HAPAG LLOYD HOUSE
column168: The ISO Container SCZU8762600 with IMDG Cargo UN1221 was loaded on M.V. Bonn Express at 0100 hrs on 16th March 2013 at an under deck position (090204). At 0200 hrs, strong fumes were felt on deck. This was reported by the duty officer (second Officer) to chief officer & all stevedores & ship staff were asked to leave the area. At 0220 hrs after securing the area Master was informed by the chief Officer. After checking the Emergency Schedules from IMDG code, Terminal representative & Local agent informed and were requested to summon expert help from shore. Vessel Superintendent Mr. Robbie Menesses informed the Master at 0515 hrs that one of the stevedores had complained of some discomfort due to the fumes, the stevedore was sent to hospital for observation and he was discharged after 2 hrs as he felt normal by the time. Officers from United States Environmental Services attended to the incident, checked for the Vapour release, discharged the container to a spill containment container on the Jetty. USES (United States Environmental Services) officers discovered an unsecured internal & external valve on the ISO container, they rectified the leak by securing the valves & replacing the gasket. The small quantity spilled in the cargo hold was removed by using Sorbent pads, and cleaning the area with fresh water and environmentally safe cleaner. The contaminated Sorbent pads were taken off the vessel by USES officers for safe disposal a shore. Cleaning of the minor spillage inside the cargo hold was done by USES officers, with assistance from ship staff. All ship's crew & Terminal employees were kept away from the site of vapour release and all cleaning & discharging of the container was carried out under the guidance of USES officers, who were all using proper protective equipment & gas detectors. Please find attached report from USES officers.

column168: On March 23rd at 0940 hours, CSX Train Q69722 derailed eighteen cars near mile post Z11.5 on the Kingsport Subdivision.  As a result of the derailment, tank car ETCX 623811, load of Propionic Acid rolled over onto its side and sustained damage to the liquid line valve.  The incident was reported to CHEMTREC report #2013-03-23-00052 and Eastman Chemical, Marilyn Williams, 903 -235-8850.  CSXT Hazardous Material Managers inspected the derailed tank car and found the cause of the release was due to damaged and bent liquid line valve mounting flange bolts.  This allowed a separation between the base of the liquid line valve and manway cover plate.  The breach between the two components resulted in the loss of 1,114 gallons of product.  Re-railing crews uprighted the tank car and positioned the container in a nearby field for transfer.  The remaining contents of the rail car was then transferred into 3 highway tank trucks for delivery to destination.

column168: THIS MORNING A MINOR DGR INCIDENT OCCURRED DURING FLIGHT ON BOARD M8220/05MAR, DETAILS AS FOLLOWS:    -THIRTY MINUTES AFTER TAKE-OFF (10:00Z), THE LOAD MASTER ON A ROUTINE CHECK OF THE PALLET LOCKS, HE NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF GHASTLY SMOKE EMANATING FROM THE RELEASE VALVE OF ONE OF TWO TANK/CYLINDER CONTAINING HELIUM (REFRIGERATED LIQUID, UN1963/CLASS 2.2) HE ALSO OBSERVED THE CONDENSATION WAS FREEZING. IMMEDIATELY HE CALLED THE CAPTAIN WHO DECIDED AN EMERGENCY RETURN TO SJU.    -WHEN THE FLIGHT WAS RETURNING TO SJU, PRPA CAME TO THE TRAFFIC OFFICE TO ADVICE THE FLIGHT WAS RETURNING DUE AN EMERGENCY. IMMEDIATELY MR. WILFREDO LARA/TRAFFIC AGENT ON DUTY CALLED LOAD CONTROL TO REPORT PROBLEM, AND MR. LUIS ROSARIO CALLED ME AND PEDRO.    -UPON ARRIVING AND DOCKING AT SJU THE CREW WAS MET BY THE FIRE BRIGADE AND OTHER AIRPORT EMERGENCY AUTHORITIES. A FEW MINUTES LATER MR. JUAN BULTED/FAA DGR INSPECTOR ARRIVED AND MET WITH US AND THE CAPTAIN.    -MIKE NEWPHER CALLED MR.LARA TO REVIEW AND DISCUSS THE DOCUMENTATION. HE ASSURED MR. LARA THE THIS GAS RELEASE WAS NORMAL.    -DGR INSPECTOR CHECKED EVERY SINGLE DOCUMENT AND FOUND IN GOOD ORDER. IN A CONFERENCE CALL WITH US, HE ALSO SPOKE TO THE SHIPPER AND OWNER. HE AGREED TO MEET WITH THEM TODAY.
column169: MR. JOHN DIAZ PRAXAIR ENGINEER SUGGEST TO MAINTAIN THE RELEASE VALVE OPEN IN ORDER THAT PRESSURE VALVE RELEASE THE EXCESS AMOUNT OG GAS PRESSURE EQUILVALENT TO 1.5PSI.    IT IS NORMAL ON THIS TYPE OF CYLINDER THAT THE PRESSURE VALVE RELEASE SMALL AMOUNT OF GAS TO LOWER THE PRESSURE INSIDE OF THE CYLINDER.
column172: Cylinder, a pressure vessel for compressed gases

column168: DRIVER MAKING A ROUTINE STOP AND CHECKING LOAD SECUREMENT OF NON-BULK DRUMS NOTICED A SMALL LEAK ON FLOOR OF TRAILER. ALL TRAILERS ARE EQUIPMENT WITH DIKE BOARDS AND METAL FLOORS TO CONTAIN LEAKS. WAS ABLE TO CONTAIN LEAK WITH OIL DRY SPILL KIT, NOTIFIED DISPATCH AND BROKER. WAITED TO CONFIRM LEAK WAS DRY AND THEN CONTINUED TO DESIGNATED FACILITY. CHECKED CONTENTS OF LOAD SEVERAL TIMES WHILE IN-TRANSIT, EVEN WENT THROUGH A SCALE-HOUSE INSPECTION STATION WITHOUT ANY INCIDENTS TO REPORT. AFTER ARRIVING AT CLEAN HARBORS THE TRUCK WAS PARKED ON A HILL WAITING TO BACK INTO A DOCK TO UNLOAD. WHEN THE BACK DOOR WAS OPENED IT WAS DISCOVERED THE MATERIAL WAS LEAKING AGAIN FROM A DRUM. THE HAZ-MAT TEAM UNLOADED THE TRUCK AND CLEANED UP SPILL. IT WAS DISCOVERED A NAIL PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. THE DRUMS WERE STACKED ONTO A PALLET WITH NAILS FACING UPWARDS. SINCE IT WAS A PINHOLE IT WAS ABLE TO BE CONTAINED WITH A SPILL KIT WHILE IN-TRANSIT.
column169: CUSTOMER WAS INFORMED TO VERIFY THAT ALL NAILS ARE REMOVED FROM PALLETS AND TO USE BETTER PACKAGING TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. DRIVER WAS RETRAINED IN HM 126, LOAD SECUREMENT, AND SPILL REPORTING

column168: At 12:50pm, while conducting a transfer of Diisobuytlene from railcar to a staged tanker trailer, operator Tim Mosher left the top of the portable platform pump, while it read 7,000 gallons, to sit inside the Ford Ranger service vehicle to escape the elements (ambient temp. 20° F Low/32° F High, and 50 mph wind gusts).  The service vehicle was parked approximately 20 feet away from the transfer, with the ignition turned off and a line of sight to the pumps meter counter.  Mr. Mosher drifted off to sleep while in the vehicle, and when he came to, he realized that the tanker trailer's capacity was exceeded and product was accumulating in the carsh box and releasing onto the underlying gravel and dirt surface.  Mr. Mosher exited the vehicle and pushed the emergency stop on the pumps main control panel, at the base of the unit.  The pump was successfully stopped and Mr. Mosher immediately notified supervisor Bill Clark of the release via radio.  All onsite transfer activity was suspended and ER activities commenced.  The estimated product loss was 700 gallons.
column169: - Operator Tim Moshier was terminated due to his negligent behavior and failure to abide by established procedure (e.g., staying in attendance of a transfer and being attentive and in control of the transfer).     - Add to monthly safety observations listing check to ensure that operators are in attendance of the transfer and attentive.    - Retrain employees on the importance of staying in attendance of the transfer, while also being attentive and in control of the transfer.    - Compose vapor “T” fitting adapter to effectively utilize an outage alarm on the trailer’s false dome.    - Have warning signs fabricated by a local vendor which state “Absolutely” No Smoking; No Cell Phones; No Electronic Devises; No Vehicle Ignitions Sources within 25’ of the transfer area.  These are to be posted on the base of the flammable portable platform pumps and barricades.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While entering customer location, truck struck a post, which damaged fuel line.  Approximately 20 gallons of gasoline were released to the concrete surface, snow covered soil adjacent to lot, and migrated into a nearby storm drain on site.  Site was secured and Terra Contracting was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, Terra Contracting applied absorbent material to the free liquid, and inspected the impacted storm drain.  A minimal amount of fuel was detected within catch basin, and was contained to immediate area.  Upon inspection of drainage system, and downgradient storm drain, no gasoline was detected.  Terra Contracting recovered the spent absorbent material, shoveled the contaminated snow/soil adjacent to lot, and removed sediment and debris from within storm drain catch basin.  Waste was containerized into five (5) 55-gallon drums, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.

column168: • The Vehicle was traveling on CA 73 South @ Post Mile 10.5 when it hit a dip in the roadway, veered, left the roadway, rolled three times across the central median and came to rest in the oncoming lanes.  • There were two Distributor Operations,Inc.employees in the vehicle. Both Team Members were taken from the scene in ambulances.One Team Member was released from the hospital that evening, and the other the following day. Injuries were cuts abrasions and concussions.  • There were 203 Batteries, Wet, Filled with Acid on board at the time of the incident containing approximately 850 gallons of sulfuric battery acid. The majority of these batteries were broken with about half being thrown from the vehicle during the accident.  • At the time of the incident the vehicle was traveling at 63 MPH.the posted speed limit was 65 MPH. We verified the speed at the time of the crash through our fleet tracking device.  • The vehicle had a Gross Vehicle Weight Rating of 26,0001bs. At the time of the incident, the total weight of the vehicle and cargo was approximately 23,0001bs.  • Witnesses at the scene indicated that the vehicle was not driving erratically and seemed to just lose control at a point where there is a dip in the roadway.  • Representatives from the following departments were at the scene: CALTRAN, CADOT, Fire Department and the California Highway Patrol. Patriot Environmental Services was called to the scene and facilitated the cleanup. All debris and contamination was removed from the scene and disposed of correctly.
column169: We will have some additional training for drivers and others employed in the company focusing on: Skid Control, Avoiding Road Hazards and Uneven Roadways.    Additionally, we will notify the city and state regarding the potential road hazard.

column168: 20FT ISO TANK, TCLU9016808 WAS DISCHARGED OFF THE VESSEL ON AT A CHASSIS. THE DRIVER WAS PARKING THE TANK WHEN HE NOTICED THE TANK WAS LEAKING. HE NOTIFIED MANAGEMENT AND LEFT THE TANK PARKED. THE AREA IS ALL CONCRETE. THE PORT OF HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. AREA WAS SECURED. APM REQUESTED M&M PROTECTION TO RESPOND AND CHECK THE TANK.ABSORBENT WAS PLACED ON THE OPPOSITE OF THE CONTAINER STACK TO ENSURE NO MATERIAL FLOWED. A POOL WAS PLACED UNDER THE TANK. THE PRODUCT SEEMED TO SLOW DOWN TO A DRIP AND EVENTUALLY NOT DRIPPING. M&M CLEANED UP THE PRODUCT ON THE GROUND WHICH WAS THOUGHT TO BE 5-10 GALLONS. M&M WAS RELEASED BY BASF AT 10:00 AM AS THEY DECIDED TO CONTRACT GARNER ENVIROMENTAL TO ASSIST IF NEEDED. IT APPEARED THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM INTERNAL FLANGE. BASF WAS NOTIFIED. BASF REPRESENTATIVES CAME ON SIGHT. THE TRANSFER TEAM FROM BISHOP, TEXAS ARRIVED APPROXIMATELY 18:00. THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED BY 21:07. THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO GESU8097421. THE AREA WAS MONITORED AND LEL READINGS TAKEN BY POHA FIRE DEPARTMENT. BASF AND GARNER CONTINUED TAKING READING BEFORE AND DURING THE TRANSFER. THE CONTAINER WAS DISCHRAGED OFF THE VESSEL AND THE PORT FIRE DEPARTMENT CHECKED THE VESSEL TO DETERMINE IF ANY PRODUCT HAD LEAKED ON THE VESSEL BUT NOTHING WAS FOUND. THE VALVE APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN DAMAGED. IT IS UNKNOWN FOR SURE HOW THE VALVE WAS DAMAGED. THERE WAS NO HOLES OR CRACKS. GARNER WAS ASKED BY BASF TO HANDLE DISPOSAL OF ABSORBENT AND ALL CLEAN UP MATERIALS. I SPOKE WITH USCG REPRESENTATIVE AT 0800 AND 1100 AM REGARDING THE INCIDENT. IT WAS REPORTED AN AREA UNDER THE CARNE MAY HAVE PRODUCT, EMPLOYEES WERE REMOVED UNTIL POHA FIRE DEPARTMENT CHECKED THE AREA AND ADVISED IT WAS CLEAR TO WORK.
column169: WE DO NOT KNOW THE DEFINITE CAUSE OF THE DAMAGE OR WHERE IT WAS DAMAGED. UPON REVIEW OF THE CHASSIS, A SUGGESTED MODIFICATION WAS MADE WHICH MAY REDUCE THE RISK OF TANK DAMAGE DURING HANDLING. THERE ARE ALOT OF VARIATIONS IN TANKS. ON SOME TANKS (NOT THIS PARTICULAR TANK)THERE IS OPEN SPACE THAT MAYBE A BAR COULD BE ADDED TO THE UNDERNEATH FRAME TO PREVENT ANYTHING FROM COMING IN CONTACT WITH A VALVE. SOME TANKS DESIGN VALVES THAT EXTEND BEYOND THE FRAME, VALVES SHOULD NEVR PROTUDE BEYOND FRAMES. AGAIN NOT THIS DESIGN, JUST IN GENERAL.

A BNSF train was stopped on main track after its crew was alerted by a wayside dragging equipment detector alarm. No defects were found after the train conductor inspected the train consist. This train was restarted and subsequently went into an emergency brake application. Train inspection revealed two rail cars derailed upright. The cause of the derailment was attributed to the cross level of track irregular, not at joints. Derailed equipment included entrained residue tank UTLX 645913 which incurred a damaged bottom outlet valve assembly (BOV) from contact with its leading truck/wheel set (A-end) that disengaged. The BOV was sheared off below its mounting flange with the internal valve closure remaining intact in the closed position. Residue commodity dripped from the damaged BOV orifice. A catch receptacle was placed under UTLX 645913 to capture commodity drips from the damaged BOV area. UTLX 645913 was cleaned and purged of hazardous material and is awaiting disposition to a designated qualified repair facility. The tank car cleaning rinseate is earmarked for appropriate disposal. A small area of impacted ballast and ground spillage is earmarked for remediated in the near future

column168: ARRIVED 2:30 PM, BUT TRAILOR IN RECEIVING DOOR ABOUT 3 PM. SHUT OFF ELIGIBLE CHOKED WHEELS WANT INSIDE TO DOCK. FORKLIFT DRIVER REMOVED ONE OF FOURT TOTES BEING DELIVERED. I WAS STANDING OUTSIDE OF TRAILOR ON THE DOCK, FORKLIFT DRIVER ENTERED TRAILOR FOR SECOND TIME, WHEN HE STARTED TO BACK OUT WITH THE SECOND TOTE, THERE WAS A LOUD SNIP. I NOTICED FLUID RUNNING OUT OF TRAILOR AND FORKLIFT DRIVER SAID SOMETHING ABAOUT A LEAD AND SHUT OFF THE FORKLIFT INSIDE OF TRAILOR. I WENT INSIDE TRAILOR TO SEE WHAT HAPPENED. I SAW THE VALVE TO THE TOTE LAYING ON FLOOR OF TRAILOR. TRYED TO BUT THE VALVE BACK ON TOTE,VALVE STEM WAS BROKEN, COULD NOT BE FIXED. LIFT TRAILOR TO GO TO TRACTER TO GET ME PHONE TO CALL SAFETY. FORKLIFT DRIVER LEFT TO GET HELP AND TO FINED SOMETHING TO PLUG LEAK.     FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED. FIRE DEPARTMENT SHOWED UP AND EVACUATED THE AREA. GOT TRUK BACK ABOUT 5 PM. FORKLIFT DRIVE SAID TO THE FIRE CAPTAIN THAT HE WAS NOT AN EMPLOYEE, JUST HELPING HIS SON.
column169: ADDITIONAL FORKLIFT OPERATOR TRAINING IS NEEDED FOR THE PERSON WHO OPERATED THE FORKLIFT.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: Roseville railyard carman reported an odor of ammonia and Hazmat Manager Johnson responded.  While inspecting rail cars the SHPX221972 was located with a leak.  Roseville Fire Dept. responded for assistance and made a level A entry to inspect the tank car.  While on top of the SHPX221972 the A end liquid valve was turned a half turn to close the valve.  The B end liquid valve was turned a half turn to close the valve and the vapor valve was turned a half turn to close the valve, stopping the release of all product.  Roseville Fire monitored with air monitoring equipment and confirmed there was no longer a release of product occurring before closing the protective housing and getting off of the tank car.  The SHPX221972 was inspected again on 03/18/2013 to confirm the tank car was not releasing product and everything checked out good.  The car was released for movement.
column169: I spoke to the Shipper and advised there unloading procedure be reviewed and all cars be re-checked to confirm valves closed properly.

column168: On March 22, 2013, during the examination of export documents offered for transport. The carrier (Seaboard Marine) noticed on an invoice that container SMLU785152-4 was carrying non-hazardous as well as hazardous cargo (UN 1950 AEROSOLS). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded. We immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. The same day, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and afterward released for transportation

column168: Five 55 Gallon containers (approximately 250 Gallons) of a foam suppression material were initially loaded into the tanker.  A second material (flammable liquid) was then loaded into the vacuum tanker truck. The agitation of the materials caused an extreme foaming event.  The foam was sucked into the vacuum vent at the top of the tanker causing the material to be discharged onto the ground.  Floor dry was utilized to contain and clean up the material.
column169: The materials should not have been loaded together.  A more formal review process will be utilized to identify potential chemical incompatible materials prior to loading.  In the future, the process will require multiple approvals from the Veolia facility chemist and EH&S Manger.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: GATX 70618 (L/NON-ODORIZED LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS) was observed venting from the top at CN Mays Yard, Harahan, LA. All appropriate depatments notified, railcar isolated.  Upon closer inspection, moisture was observed in the safety relief valve assembly.  The outage was checked and the magnetic ball gauging device rod was allowed to rise past the ruler marking and stopped at 7 inches.  The pressure was checked and showed 252 psi.  The railcar was determined to be overloaded by volume. Shipper's response team reduced product by transferring approx 4,835 gallons into a tank truck.  Upon completion of this transfer the outage on the railcar was 23 inches and pressure was 80 psi. Railcar released for movement to destination by shipper.
column169: No additional comments.

Train YKHSO4-29, derailed 35 cars which included 11 dangerous goods tank cars in CN Kirk Yard, Gary, Indiana. The tank cars involved included  PPGX 3384, GATX 12588, SHPX 207933, UTLX 66400, SBLX 24016, GATX 45034 all R/ Sodium Hydroxide UN1824, UTLX 663769, R/ Naphthalene, Molten UN3257, NATX 2053 and UTLX 671024 both L/ Phthalic Anhydride UN3257. All were noted with jacket damage and/or minor tank damage. None of the listed cars lost product or damaged to an extent of possible product loss.  ACFX 73845 R/ Naphthalene, Molten - UN3257, suffered a puncture through the outer jacket and into the tank shell on the BR side of the car from a double shelf coupler of an adjacent tank car. Product was solidified prior to the incident, resulting in no release. Car UTLX 204306, L/ Petroleum Distillates, N.O.S. UN1268, rolled onto its top resulting in the protective housing being displaced and the liquid line valve threaded pipe to the tank car body cracking, which allowed approximately 50 gallons of product to be released. Leak was stopped and the product was transferred.

column168: DRIVER OF V1 (CMV) WAS TRAVELLING WEST IN RIGHT LANE OF I-80 WHEN HE APPARENTLY BLACKED OUT. V1 TRAVELLED OFF NORTH SIDE OF I-80 AND CONTINUED 168' IN WESTERLY DIRECTION PARALLEL WITH ROADWAY. V1 THEN PARTIALLY SCALED THE ADJACENT EMBANKMENT, TRAVELLED 128' BEFORE DESCENDING SAID EMBANKMENT AND CONTINUING WESTERLY PARALLEL WITH ROADWAY FOR DISTANCE OF 466' BEFORE ROLLING TO ITS LEFT ONE-HALF REVOLUTION. BOTH TRUCK AND TRAILER CAME TO REST ON ITS ROOF/TOP 7' OFF NORTH EDGE OF I-80 WEST FACING WESTERLY DIRECTION. EMERGENCY AND ENVIROMENTAL CREWS REPSONDED. TANK SHELL WAS SPLIT/CRACKED APPROXIMATELY 3 INCHES AND SMALL LEAK WAS DISCOVERED AT THE UPPER RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRAILER. BEFORE LEAK WAS STOPPED, DURATION OF RELEASE WAS LESS THAN 30 MINUTES. EMERGENCY RESPONDERS PLACED EPOXY PUTTY OVER THE SPLIT/CRACK. 200 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WERE LOST. ENVIROMENTAL CREWS REMOVED SURROUNDING SOIL/WATER/PRODUCT MIXTURE TO PREVENT GROUNDWATER CONTAMINATION.
column169: CRAWFORD TRANSPORTERS WILL PROVIDE MORE EDUCATION TO DRIVERS SO THAT HE/SHE CAN BETTER DETERMINE HIS/HER FITNESS FOR DUTY BEFORE LEAVING HOME FOR AN EXTENDED PERIOD AND BEFORE STARTING EACH DAY. EDUCATIONAL MATERIALS WILL INCLUDE INFORMATION ON WHY IT IS IMPERATIVE TO ASSESS FITNESS FOR DUTY, ON PREVENTIVE CARE, ON RECOGNIZING THE SIGNS ANS SYMPTOMS OF CERTAIN MEDICAL CONDITIONS, ILLNESSES AND FATIGUE, ON HOW TO SEEK TREATMENT, AND ON STEPS TO TAKE IF A DRIVER DETERMINES HE/SHE IS UNFIT FOR DUTY. BEFORE ASSIGNING LOADS, DISPATCH WILL ASK DRIVERS ABOUT HIS/HER FITNESS FOR DUTY AND WILL NEVER FORCE OR INTIMIDATE A DRIVER INTO ACCEPTING A LOAD IF HE/SHE FEELS UNFIT FOR DUTY.

column168: DSR was unloading a trailer and called me (FOS) over.  Reported to me that he pulled the skid off, and noticed some chemical substance leaking out.  There was no evidence of a fork puncture, but I noticed a dent on the drum.  DSR says he found skid in that condition.  We removed the shrink-wrap and lifted the suspected leaking skid and found a pinhole on the bottom edge. We placed the defective drum in a plastic wrap, in a salvage drum.  Cleaned up in house.

DSR entered the trailer with a 15 foot by 6 inch piece of steel. He had it on the end of his forks and while he was working the steel into the trailer it fell off and hit the bottom of a drum. The hole is the size of a half-dollar. In addition, about five to 10 gallons leaked on the floor of the trailer. It leaked for about 5 minutes. As soon as it happened both FOSs on the dock were informed and they informed the FOM. The FOM then called the chemical spill number where they said it was safe to clean up ourselves. While wearing gloves, to stop the leaking, a DSR moved the barrel so the hole was on top and the leaking stopped. Then absorbent was put down on the trailer floor and underneath the trailer. The drum and all the containments were then placed in a salvage drum  located in the Hazmat Bay.

During a tank car blitz in the North Little Rock,AR yard UP Haz Mat personnel found TILX 199632 with a vapor release from a loose manway cover.  2 of 8 bolts were less than tool tight resulting in the release.  The pressure was released from the car, the manway opened and the gasket inspected.  The gasket was found to be in good condition and the manway properly secured.  The car was released back into transportation.  This was a vapor release with no liquid release.

column168: During humping operations in the railyard, tank car DBUX 300314 failed to stop after being humped and rolled out of the bowl tracks sideswiping a cut of rail cars occupying the lead track. DBUX 300314 derailed on its side with its top valve housing cover damaged during the derailment. The liquid line valve under the valve housing cover sustained damage and was partially dislodged at its mounting flange allowing commodity to escape. Mechanical responders plugged the exposed liquid line orifice which stopped the commodity release. The cause of the roll-out was attributed to a defective retarder yard skate. DBUX 300314 was rerailed by 1030 hrs. CDT, 3/30/2013. All commodity within DBUX 300314 was transferred to another suitable tank car without incident by 0230 hrs. CDT, 4/06/2013. DBUX 300314 was power washed/steam cleaned of all hazardous material on 4/09/2013. Captured spillage was vacuumed and impacted ground spillage was excavated and earmarked for appropriated disposal.

column168: This incident involved a cargo tank trailer with 4 compartments with the following capacities: - Compartment 1 Capacity 4500* (The release involved Compartment 1)   - Compartment 2 Capacity 1500  - Compartment 2 Capacity 2000   - Compartment 2 Capacity 3500  The driver was delivering a load of #2 Dyed Diesel Fuel to the bulk plant for Mouse River Oil Company. The driver arrived at the location and went out and hooked up his hoses. When the driver was all done hooking up, he entered the truck to do his paperwork. When the driver heard his compartment go empty, so he stepped out of the truck and saw that his hose had come off. The driver shut the pump down and immediately called the customer, Shop Foreman, and Safety Director. Our company immediately contacted our emergency response personnel/cleanup company. The estimated time of discharge was about 10 minutes. We are still waiting to receive the total dollar amounts for the costs for cleanup and property damages.
column169: The changes we have made include putting ear clips in the cam locks to prevent accidental hose disconnect. We are also emphasizing the procedures drivers must follow during loading and unloading operations through additional driver training.

The cargo tank did not fail. A release resulted when the product transfer hose connection coupling separated during the unloading process. The Driver completed the pre-fill procedures, and started the unloading process. The product transfer hose connection coupling separated from the customer fill connection, releasing product for approximately 5 seconds. The Driver terminated the fill using the emergency stop switch on the vehicle, immediately reported the incident and returned to his home facility. The transfer hose and customer fill connection were inspected and it was determined, that a broken weld at the "flare" connection caused the hose to separate during the unloading process. The product transfer hose fill connection was replaced immediately.
column169: Will continue annual inspections and testing of cargo tank product transfer hose and connector couplings.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Human Error
column168: ON MARCH 5,2013 AN EAST PENN LOGISTICS, LLC TRACTOR PULLED INTO A PETRO STOPPING CENTER IN PERRYSBURG, OHIO. WHEN THE DRIVER OF THE TRACTOR CAME BACK OUT TO HIS TRUCK HE NOTICED THAT THE LOAD WAS LEAKING. WHEN HE OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR, HE SAW SMOKE. WHEN THE SMOKE CLEARED HE NOTICED A SMALL FIRE AT THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO PUT THE FIRE OUT WITH HIS FIRE EXTINGUISHER THAT HE CARRIES ON THE TRUCK. THE LOCAL POLICE AND THE FIRE COMPANY WERE CALLED TO THE INCIDENT. THE DRIVER CALLED BACK TO HIS EMPLOYER, EAST PENN MFG CO, LYONS STATION TO REPORT HIS INCIDENT. WHEN THE FIRE COMPANY ARRIVED THEY CHECKED THE TRAILER TO MAKE SURE THAT THE FIRE WAS INDEED OUT. THEY FIRE COMPANY DID INFORM EAST PENN THAT THEY COULD NOT HELP IN THE CLEAN UP OF THE SPILL THAT WE NEEDED A HAZ MAT CREW TO DO SO. EMS, AN ENVIROMENTAL FIRM WAS CALLED TO ASSIST IN THE CLEAN UP. THEY ARRIVED WITHIN THE HOUR.   EMS UNLOADED THE TRAILER. THE UNDAMAGED SPENT LEAD ACID BATTERIES WERE PUT TO THE SIDE TO BE RE-LOADED. THE DAMAGED/BURNT SPENT LEAD ACID BATTERIES WERE PUT INTO GAYLORD BOXES TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE. THEY WERE PLACED  INTO THE GAYLORD VERY CONSCIOUSLY TO PREVENT THE TERMINAL FROM TOUCHING TO PREVENT ARCHING. A LAYER OF CARDBOARD WAS PUT BETWEEN EACH LAYER OF BATTERIES. BOTH THE UNDAMAGED AND REPACKAGED BATTERIES WERE LOADED BACK INTO THE TRAILER TO CONTINUE TO ITS DESTINATION TO EAST PENN MANUFACTURING, LYONS STATION FOR THE RECYLING OF THE BATTERIES AT ITS SECONDARY LEAD SMELTER.  SODA ASH WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE AND ABSORB THE ACID THAT WAS SPILLED IN THE TRAILER AND WHAT HAD LEAKED OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER. ALL SODA ASH WAS PICKED UP AND PUT INTO OVER PACK DRUMS ALONG WITH ANY PIECES OF ACID SOAKED WOOD,CARDBOARD AND STRETCH WARP. EMS IS HAVING THE CONTAINERS TESTED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. AT THIS TIME, IT IS UNCLEAR EXACTLY HOW THE FIRE BEGAN. IT IS ASSUMED THAT TERMINALS ON THE BATERRIES GOT IN CONTACT WITH ONE ANOTHER CAUSING A CHARGE, CREATING THE FIRE.
column169: PROPER PACKAGING TECHNIQUES OF SPENT LEAD ACID BATTERIES WILL BE REVIEWED WITH ALL THE SHIPPERS AT ALL OF EAST PENN'S WAREHOUSES. WORK INSTRUCTIONS WILL BE REVIEWED TO MAKE SURE THEY COVER THE PROPER PACKAGING OF SPENT LEAD BATTERIES IN ACCORDANCE TO 49 CFR 173.159(A) AND 173.159 (E). IF NEEDED, WORK INSTRUCTIONS WILL BE UPDATED. PACKAGING WILL BE ALSO BE REVIEWED WITH THE TRUCK DRIVERS.

column168: THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED DUE TO A TIRE/BRAKE FIRE CAUSED WHEN THE RIGHT, REAR, INSIDE TRAILER TIRE BLEW OUT. SOME PIECES OF RUBBER GOT WEDGED INTO THE RIGHT FRONT BRAKE DRUM, GOT HOT AND BEGAN TO BURN. DRIVER TIRED TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE BUT EXHAUSTED HIS FIRE EXTINGUISHER. TRAILER REAR END COMPLETELY BURNED WHILE FIRE DEPARTMENT FROM NEAR-BY TOWN WAS CALLED AND CAME TO THE SCENE. ALL 8 TRAILER TIRES BURNED UP. TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH LIQUID NITROGEN AND TOO HEAVY FOR WRECKER TO LIFT. MISSISSIPPI EPA WAS NOTIFIED AND WE REQUESTED PERMISSION FROM THEM TO INTENTIALLY RELEASE THE LOAD OF NITROGEN SO TRAILER COULD BE REMOVED FROM SHOULDER OF ROAD. PERMISSION WAS GRANTED AND PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AS LIQUID AND VENTED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE WHILE MS STATE PATROL RE-ROUTED TRAFFIC. ONCE PRODUCT WAS GONE, TRAILER WAS HOOKED TO A WRECKER AND REMOVED FROM THE ROADSIDE. THERE WAS NO CLEAN-UP AS THE NITROGEN VAPORIZED AND RETURNED TO THE ATMOSPHERE.
column169: THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED NOT DUE TO A VESSEL FAILURE, BUT DUE TO A MECHANICAL FAILURE. A TIRE BLEW OUT FOR SOME REASON. IT COULD HAVE BEEN THE TIRE, THE BEARING ON THE AXLE, OR THE BRAKE DRUM THAT GOT HOT AND CAUSED THE BLOWOUT. TRAINING SHOULD STRESS TO BOTH DRIVERS AND MECHANICS THE IMPORTANCE OF PROPER PREVENTATIVE MAINTENANCE AND PROPER DAILY, MONTHLY, AND ANNUAL INSPECTIONS.

column168: EMI JOB #33821: MR. TIRSO BELTRAIN OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INC. (EMI) RECEEIVED A CALL FROM MR. ABEL STROSE OF CON-WAY TRUCKLOAD, INC. (CTI). MR. STROSE REPORTED THAT A CTI TRACTOR-TRAILER (BOX VAN) UNIT HAD BEEN INVOLVED IN A MULTI VEHICLE ACCIDENT DUE TO A DUST STORM. THE CTI UNIT WAS TRANSPORTING A LOAD OF BATTERIES, ACID LIQUID (SULFURIC ACID), AND MISCELLANEOUS BATTERY ACCESSORIES. MR. STROSE REPORTED THAT THE LOAD OF BATTERIES HAD SHIFTED FORWARD WHEN THE CTI TRACTOR UNIT (MILTON BARROW-DRIVER) IMPACTED THE REAR OF ANOTHER TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT. IT WAS REPORTED THAT SOME OF THE BATTERIES HAD BROKEN THROUGH THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER AND SPILLED ONTO THE ROADWAY. MR. STROSE REQUESTED THAT ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT COORDINATE A RESPONSE TO THE RELEASE. MR. BELTRAIN CONTACTED ECO-LOGICAL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (ELES), AN EMI APPROVED ENVIRONMENTAL SUBCONTRACTOR. MR. BELTRAIN REQUESTED THAT ELES MOBILIZE PERSONNEL TO THE INCIDENT SITE TO REMOVE THE DAMAGED BATTERIES FROM THE ROADWAY WHILE EMI ASSEMBELED A RESPONSE TEAM AND MOBILIZED TO THE SITE. ELES ARRIVED ON SITE AND BEGAN CLEANUP ACTIVITIES. THE DAMAGED BATTERIES WERE REMOVED FROM THE ROADWAY. THE DAMAGED BATTERIES WERE PLACED ON TWO PALLETS SHRINK WRAPPED. T-MILLER WRECKER SERVICE THEN TOWED THE UNIT TO A SECURED AREA APPROXIMATELY 0.5 MIILES WEST OF THE INCIDENT SITE JUST OFF THE SERVICE ROAD. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL ARRIVED AT THE SITE WHERE THE UNIT WAS LOCATED. ELES INFORMED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT THAT THE WRECKER SERVICE HAD TRANSPORTED THE TWO (2) PALLETS OF DAMAGED BATTERIES TO THEIR FACILITY LOCATED IN AMARILLO, TEXAS. IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE PALLETIZED BATTERIES HAD SHIFT FORWARD AND BROKE THROUGH THE LOWER LEFT CORNER OF THE NORE OF THE TRAILER. THE SEAL (#247930) WAS REMOVED FROM THE REAR DOORS OF THE TRAILER. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL MADE ENTRY TO INSPECT THE TRAILER. IT WAS OBSERVED THAT SOME OF THE PALLETIZED BATTERIES WERE STILL INTACT. BECAUSE OF DARKNESS IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL WOULD RETURN IN THE MORNING DURING DAYLIGHT HOURS TO START THE CLEANUP. SODA ASH AND CLAY ABSORBENTS WERE APPLIED INSIDE THE TRAILER TO PREVENT ANY LIQUIDS FROM MIGRATING OUT OF THE TRAILER. THE TRAILER WAS SECURED AND ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL DEPARTED THE SITE. ON SUNDAY, 03-24-13, ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL RETURNED TO THE SITE. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL BEGAN INSPECTING THE LOAD AND SEPARATED THE UNDAMAGED BATTERIES FROM THE DAMAGED BATTERIES. THE UNDAMAGED BATTERIES WERE WIPED CLEAN THEN PLACED ON PALLETS, SHRINK WRAPPED THE LABELED. CTI PROVIDED ANOTHER TRAILER AND THE UNDAMAGED BATTERIES WERE LOADED INTO THE 2ND TRAILER. ALL DAMAGED BATTERIES WERE PLACED INTO 95-GALLON POLY OVERPACK DRUMS. TWELVE (12) 95-GALLON POLY OVERPACKS (CONTAINING DAMAGED BATTERIES) AND FOURTEEN (14) 55-GALLON DRUM PLASTIC LINERS OF TRASH AND DEBRI (USED PPE, CARDBOARD, AND PLASTIC) WERE GENERATED. THE OVERPACK DRUMS AND THE DRUM LINER

column168: TRUCK TRACTOR #680, HAULING TANK TRAILER #P546 WITH PROPANE WERE TRAVELING NORTH BOUND ON FM468. THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF VEHICLE ON A CURVE, ROLLED OVER AND SLID OFF THE ROADWAY ON THE WEST BAR DITCH WHERE IT STRUCK A HIGH FENCE AND UTILITY POLE WHICH CAUSED A CRACK OF ABOUT 2 INCHES LONG ON THE FRONT LEFT OF TANK HEAD AND WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING PRESSURE. TRACTOR AND TANK CAME TO REST ON ITS RIGHT FACING NORTHEAST THEREFORE THE CRACK WAS FACING UP.  IN HOUSE TEAM HELPED MITIGATE THE RISK OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RELEASE BY TRANSFERRING THE LIQUID TO EMPTY TANK #109, WHILE IT WAS STILL LAYING ON ITS RIGHT SIDE. OBTAINING APPROXIMATELY 53% OF THE LIQUID. THEN THE TANK WAS LIFTED UPRIGHT TO ENABLE TO TRANSFER THE REST OF THE PRODUCT. TRANSFERRING A TOTAL OF 80%. THEN THE PRESSURE WAS RELIEVED FROM TANK DUE TO THE CRACK.    DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL FOR INJURY TREATMENT  THERE WAS AN EVACUATION OF ABOUT 1 MILE RADIUS AND ROAD CLOSURE FROM I-35 TO FM468 AND HWY 85 FOR MORE THAN 5 HOURS.  THERE WAS A DIESEL SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS. ENVIROMENTAL SERVICES WERE CONTRACTED TO REMEDIATE THE SITE WHICH INCLUDED EXCAVATION, REMOVAL, TRANSPORTATION AND PROPER DISPOSAL OF CONTAMINATED SOIL.  ACCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO RAILROAD COMMISSION OF TEXAS AS WELL AS TEXAS COMMISSION ON ENVIROMENTAL QIUALITY.   TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE TOWED AWAY AND SENT FOR REPAIR AND RE-CERTIFICATION.  THERE WAS NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RELEASED EXCEPT PRESSURE.

column168: Vehicle was traveling southbound on Interstate 27 at mile post 15.Vehicle was traveling approximately 70mph in the inside lane of a two lane roadway. Vehicle then struck the inside guard rail. After several hundred feet, the vehicle breached the guard rail. Vehicle entered into the center median and then went over an embankment and dropped approximately 20 feet. vehicle impacted the roadway below and the load was throw through the box van on the truck. The batteries were thrown onto the roadway and ruptured. The only injuries that occurred was minor injuries the driver received as a result of the motor vehicle accident. The batteries were all sealed units and the package failure was due to the impact with the roadway and when it breached the box van of the truck. Many batteries were destroyed and many more were cracked, split opened. New Deal fire department responded and freed the driver from the vehicle. Texas DPS inspected the vehicle. A professional emergency response clean up company responded. They cleaned the scene and disposed of the waste according to all federal laws.

column168: AT 7 AM, HILLIS TRANSPORT ARRIVED ON SITE AT JOHNSON'S 66 STATION, LOCATED AT 100 WEST MAIN ST., PORTAGEVILLE, MO TO DOWNLOAD FUEL. THE HILLIS TANKERS TRUCK PARKED ON THE WEST SIDE OF HUFFMAN AVENUE, ADJACENT TO JOHNSON'S, FACING NORTH. AT 7:10 AM THE DRIVER STARTED DOWNLOADING FUEL. AT APPROXIMATELY 7:15 AM, THE DRIVER COULD HEAR LIQUID HITTING THE GROUND NEAR THE TRANSPORT TANKER. WHEN THE DRIVER CHECKED THE TANKER, HE FOUND FUEL SPILLING OUT OF THE BACKSIDE OF THE TRANSFER PUMP. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE PUMP DOWN AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED. FREE PHASE LIQUID POOLED ON THE WEST SIDE OF HUFFMAN AVENUE AND FLOWED ACROSS TO THE EAST SIDE. SOME FUEL WORKERS IMMEDIATELY CAPPED THE STORM SEWER LINE IN A MANHOLE APPROXIMATELY 1 BLOCK DOWN GRADIENT TO PREVENT CONTINUED MIGRATION OF FREE PHASE GASOLINE. THE MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES WAS NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE AND INCIDENT #130325-0738-RLG WAS ASSIGNED. HILLIS TRANSPORT CONTRACTED SMITH & CO. ENGINEERS TO MOBILIZE TO THE SITE TO HANDLE ALL EMERGENCY RESPONSE ABATEMENT ACTIVITIES. CITY WORKERS SPREAD SILTY SOIL OVER FREE STANDING GASOLINE ALONG THE HUFFMAN AVE. RIGHT-OF-WAY TO ABATE GASOLINE VAPORS AND PREVENT CONTINUED MIGRATION OF THE FUEL INTO THE STORM SEWER. INTER-RAIL SYSTEMS, OF CAPE GIRARDEAU, MOBILIZED A VACUUM TRUCK AND RECOVERED APPROXIMATELY 2900 GALLONS OF FUEL/IMPACTED STORM WATER FROM THE CAPPED STORM SEWER LINE. THE CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT FLUSHED THE SEWER LINES ON MULTIPLE OCCASIONS UNTIL MINIMAL VAPORS WERE DOCUMENT WITHIN THE SEWER LINE. SMITH & CO. EXCAVATED IMPACTED SOIL ON BOTH SIDES OF HUFFMAN AVE. VERIFICATION SOIL SAMPLES WERE COLLECTED FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE EXCAVATION PRIOR TO BACKFILING. ANALYTICAL RESULTS OF SOIL SAMPLES COLLECTED WERE BELOW MDNR DEFAULT TARGET LEVELS. THE EXCAVATION WAS BROUGHT BACK TO GRADE WITH COMMERCIAL BASE MATERIAL AND COMPACTED IN PLACE.
column169: PRIOR TO STARTING TO DOWNLOAD FUEL, DRIVER WILL VISUALLY VERIFY THAT TRANSFER PUMP IS PROPERLY PLUGGED ON THE BACKSIDE TO PREVENT ACCIDENTAL DISCHARGE OF FUEL.

column168: ALAN HAYES RECEIVED A PHONE CALL AT 8:20 AM THIS MORNING FROM JIMMY WINGFIELD. THE PHONE LOG STATES THAT 800 GALLONS OF REGULAR GASOLINE WERE RELEASED DURING A FUEL DROP INTO THE 15,000 GALLON REGULAR GASOLINE UST AT 4:00 AM THIS MORNING. ALL PERSONS LISTED ABOVE UNDER "INDIVIDUALS CONTACTED" WERE ON SITE WHEN WE ARRIVED. DALE GREER STATED THAT THE TOWN OF MOSHEIM FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS DISPATCHED SHORTLY AFTER THE RELEASE.  DALE GREER STATED THAT IT WAS HIS UNDERSTANDING THAT THE DRIVER, STEVE RADER OF ROGERS PETROLEUM, HAD PARKED THE DELIVERY TRUCK OVER THE MIDDLE OF THE TANK PIT. THIS LOCATION HAD THE TRUCK SET UP TO DELIVER THE FUEL INTO THE REGULAR GASOLINE TANK FILL PORT, BUT BLOCKED THE DRIVER'S VIEW OF THE ATG PROBE PORT OF THE TANK WHILE HE WAS MAKING THE DELIVERY. ACCORDING TO OFFICER WYKLE'S AND MR. GREER'S ACCOUNTS, MR. RADER HEARD SOME METAL RATTLING DURING THE DELIVERY SO HE WALKED AROUND THE DELIVERY TRUCK AND WITNESSED THE RELEASE OF GASOLINE COMING FROM THE ATG PORT.  IT IS UNCLEAR AS TO WHY THE DRIVER DID NOT RECOGNIZE THAT THE BALL FLOAT VALVE RESTRICTED THE DELIVERY FLOW (WHEN THE TANK WAS AT 90% CAPACITY) PRIOR TO THE RELEASE. THE CORRELATION BETWEEN THE AMOUNT OF FUEL ON THE DELIVERY TRUCK VERSUS THE AMOUNT TO BE DELIVERED INTO THE TANK IS UNKNOWN AT THIS TIME.  THE GASOLINE FLOWED TOWARD THE PARKING LOT CURB. THERE ARE THREE DRAINAGE OVERFLOW SPOTS OR BREAKS ALONG THE CURB. ACCORDING TO OFFICER WYKLE'S STATEMENT, HE ARRIVED AT 4:14 AM, SPOKE TO THE DRIVER AND BEGAN TO WALK THE PERIMETER OF THE AREA. AT THIS TIME, TWO TOWN OF MOSHEIM FIRE DEPARTMENT UNITS ARRIVED AND THEY PROCEEDED TO APPLY ABSORBENT TO CONTAIN THE FLOW OF THE FUEL AND THE THREE DRAINAGE OVERFLOW SPOTS WERE "DIKED" TO STOP FUEL FROM FLOWING OVER THE CURBED AREA. OFFICE WYKLE THEN CALLED 911 TO DISPATCH HAZ-MAT UNITS FROM GREENEVILLE/GREENE COUNTY TO ASSIST WITH THE CLEAN-UP, JIMMY ARRIVED AT 5:20 AM. AMERICAN ENVIRONMENTAL  ARRIVED AT 7:20 AM. TIM NEAL ARRIVED AT 11:00 AM.  JIMMY AND DALE SHOWED US THE PATH THE FUEL TOOK. ONLY ONE OF THE THREE DRAINAGE OVERFLOWS (THE ONE NEAREST TO IDELL ROAD) APPEARED TO BE AFFECTED BY THE FUEL. AMERICAN ENVIRONMENTAL, WITH OVERSIGHT FROM JIMMY, EXCAVATED 30 CUBIC YARDS OF SOILS FROM THAT AREA AND PLANNED TO REMOVE MORE PRIOR TO SAMPLING. MOST OF THE FUEL FOLLOWED THE PARKING LOT ALONG THE CURB TO THE LOW SPOT NEAR THE CULVERT FOR STONY CREEK. THERE WAS A LARGE AMOUNT OF RAINFALL ON MARCH 11 AND EARLY MARCH 12 CAUSING THE CREEK TO BE SEVERAL FEET ABOVE ITS NORMAL LEVEL AT THE TIME OF THE RELEASE. TINA ROBINSON SAID SHE HAD SPOKEN WITH SOME OF THE FIRST RESPONDERS AND THEY TOLD HER THE CREEK WAS FLOWING HIGH AND AT A VERY FAST RATE OF SPEED DURING THE SPILL. THEY BELIEVE THAT THE MAJORITY OF THE FUEL WAS FLUSHED DOWNSTREAM AT A VERY HIGH FLOW RATE.  WE HAD THE MAINTENANCE CREW OPEN THE 2 OBSERVATION WELLS IN THE TANK PIT. THE WELL FURTHEST FROM THE STORE AND ROAD HAD A VAPOR READING OF 400 PPM AND THE WELL NEAREST THE DISPENSER

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS TRAVELING ON A FOUR-LANE NON-CONTROLLED ACCESS HIGHWAY WHEN TRAFFIC STARTED TO SLOW DOWN. OUR DRIVER INCREASED HIS FOLLOWING DISTANCE TO THE VEHICLE IN FRONT OF HIM WHEN ANOTHER VEHICLE SWERVED IN FRONT OF HIM AND IMMEDIATELY SLAMMED ON THE BRAKES. HE SWERVED LEFT TO MISS THE VEHICLE AND RAN OFF THE ROAD. THE AREA WHERE OUR DRIVER RAN OFF OF THE ROAD WAS A STEEP DOWNHILL GRADE AND HE LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE AND ROLLED OVER ON THE DRIVER SIDE AND SLID DOWN HILL. THE VEHICLE CAME TO REST AGAINST A TREE THAT KEPT IT FROM GOING FURTHER DOWN THE HILL. THE IMPACT FROM THE TREE CAUSED A STRUCTURAL FAILURE ON THE DOT-406 TRAILER DOME LID TO THE NUMBER 4 COMPARTMENT.     THE LEAK OCCURRED NEAR THE DOME LID ON THE NUMBER 4 COMPARTMENT. THE TRAILER SHELL IT SELF DID NOT FAIL.    I HAVE INCLUDED PHOTOS AND A REPORT FROM OUR ON-BOARD COMPUTER SYSTEM.
column169: WACCAMAW TRANSPORT CONTINUES TO USE NUMEROUS SAFETY AND TRAINING PROGRAMS TO EMPHASIZE TO DRIVERS THAT THEY SHOULD MAINTAIN THEIR LANE IN THE EVENT SOMEONE SLAMS ON BRAKES IN FRONT OF YOU. ALTHOUGH WE DO HAVE CASES WHERE HUMAN INSTINCTS TAKE OVER AND CAUSE AN UNDESIRED OUTCOME. WE EQUIP OUR TRUCKS WITH ROLLOVER STABILITY AND MANY OTHER SAFETY SYSTEMS BUT IT WOULD BE HARD FOR THOSE SYSTEMS TO PREVENT THIS TYPE OF ACCIDENT WHEN ANOTHER VEHICLE SWERVES IN FRONT OF YOU AND THEN IMMEDIATE SLAMS ON THE BRAKES.    THIS TRAILER WORKED WELL IN THIS SITUATION ONLY LOSING 40 GALLONS. AS YOU WILL SEE IN THE PHOTOS, IT SUFFERED ALOT OF DAMAGE AND WAS DEEMED A TOTAL LOSS.    RECOMMENDATION - SINCE THE FAILURE OCCURRED IN THE DOME LID, MAYBE BETTER MATERIAL IN THIS AREA WOULD HAVE ADDED MORE STABILITY.

column168: OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE EXEL PLANT AT 7:45 AND STARTED TO FILL FORKLIFT CYNLINDERS. HE FILLED APPROXIMATELY 10 CYNLINDERS WHEN HE HEARD THE SOUND OF ESCAPING GAS. HE SAW PROPANE ESCAPING FROM THE PUMP AREA OF THE TRUCK AND IMMEDIATELY USED HIS REMOTE TO SHUT DOWN THE TRUCK. THE TRUCK CONTINUED TO LEAK PRODUCT UNTIL IT EMPTIED ITSELF 11 HOURS LATER. THE DRIVER FOLLOWED PROCEDURES WITH REGARDS TO THE INCIDENT. THE WAREHOUSE WAS EVACUATED AND TRAFFIC WAS STOPPED. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND AN INCIDENT COMMAND WAS ESTABLISHED ON SITE. THE DISTRICT MANAGER WAS ON SITE AND STAYED UNTIL THE TRUCK WAS TOWED AWAY. NO MEMBERS OF THE MEDIA EVER ARRIVED. WE LOST 2040 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.    THE PUMP ON THE TRUCK BLEW A SEAL WHICH ALLOWED THE PROPANE TO ESCAPE.    THE TRUCK HAD A VK INSPECTION PERFORMED ON IT IN FEBRUARY OF 2013. AT THIS TIME THE PUMP WAS REBUILT. THE PUMP WAS DISASSEMBLED AFTER THE INCIDENT AND THERE WAS SEVERE DAMAGE TO THE SHAFT OF THE PUMP WHICH LED TO THE SEAL FAILURE. IT APPEARS THAT THE REASSEMBLY OF THE PUMP WHEN IT WAS REBUILT WAS NOT DONE CORRECTLY WHICH LED TO THE SEAL FAILURE.
column169: THE SHOP THAT REBUILT THE PUMP IS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE PUMP FAILURE DUE TO IMPROPER REASSEMBLY.

column168: SCOTT HUFFMAN TRUCKING WAS DISPATCHED FROM WILBUR-ELLIS, CENTRAL FERRY, WA PLANT WITH 52,9403 OF AQUA AMMONIA FOR FIELD DELIVERY TO MEYERS FARMS, STOUT ROAD, GENESEE, ID. DARRIN WOOD, DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 8:00 PM TO UNLOAD THE LIQUID FERTILIZER INTO A PORTABLE POLY STORAGE TANK. HE PARKED THE TRUCK ON A SLIGHT INCLINE TO UNLOAD AND CONNECTED A 20 FT HOSE TO THE TANK. THE TRUCK SLID SLIGHTLY WHEN THE TANKER WAS ALMOST EMPTY CAUSING THE VALVE ON THE STORAGE TANK TO PULL OFF ALLOWING 6600 GALLONS OF LIQUID TO EMPTY ON THE GROUND AND INTO A DRAINAGE DITCH. THE POLY STORAGE TANK WAS LOCATED ABOUT 15 FEET FROM THE DRAINAGE DITCH CULVERT, THE FERTILIZER ENTERED THE DITCH AND TRAVELLED DOWNSTREAM. WILBUR-ELLIS CONTACTED ROACH CONSTRUCTION, GENESEE, ID TO CONSTRUCT AN EARTHEN DAM 1.5 MILES FROM THE SPILL SITE TO PREVENT THE FERTILIZER FROM ENTERING COW CREEK. NRC ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, PORTALND, OR WERE CONTACTED AND ASKED TO RESPOND TO THE LOCATION TO PROVIDE CONTROL AND CLEAN-UP OF THE SPILL. WATER AND AMMONIA WERE PUMPED INTO PORTABLE POLY STORAGE TANKS AND THE TANKER TRUCK UNTIL 4:45 AM. ABOUT 72,000 GALLONS WAS REMOVED FROM THE EARTHEN DAM SITE. NRC DIRECTED ROACH CONSTRUCTION TO REMOVE THE EARTHEN DAM AT 5:00 AM. THE DIRT WAS STOCKPILED NEXT TO THE DRAINAGE DITCH ON PLASTIC AND COVERED.    NRC MONITORED THE PH LEVELS OF THE WATER THROUGHOUT THE NIGHT. NRC CONTACTED GALE OSBURN, IDAHO DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY TO OBTAIN VERBAL APPROVAL OF SITE ACTIVITIES AND DISPOSITION OF THE WASTES, LIQUIDS, AND SOLIDS. THE WATER AND SOLUTION WERE DISPOSED OF BY SCOTT HUFFMAN TRUCKING TO A FARM LOCATION IN PALOUSE, WA.
column169: SCOTT HUFFMAN TRUCKING WILL IMPROVE TRUCK EQUIPMENT BY INSTALLING ADDITIONAL SPRING BREAK CHAMBERS TO HOLD THE EQUIPMENT SECURE WHEN PARKED ON SLOPES. CONTINUE TRAINING WITH DRIVERS ON HANDLING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND EMERGENCY PROCEDURES TO ENSURE SAFETY PROCEDURES ARE FOLLOWED WHEN TRANSFERRING PRODUCT. IN ADDITION, SCOTT HUFFMAN TRUCKING WILL NOT UNLOAD INTO UNPROPERLY SET STORAGE TANKS TO AVOID RISKY SITUATIONS.
